## Introduction to DANDI:000617

**Dandiset Title:**  
Allen Institute Openscope - Sequence Learning Project

**Dandiset DOI:**  
[10.48324/dandi.000617/0.250312.0130](https://doi.org/10.48324/dandi.000617/0.250312.0130)

**Link to Dandiset:**  
[Allen Institute Openscope - Sequence Learning Project on DANDI Archive](https://dandiarchive.org/dandiset/000617/0.250312.0130)

### Description

This Dandiset contains experimental data from the Allen Institute's Sequence Learning Project, which investigates predictive computations in the neocortex of mice. Using two-photon calcium imaging, the team recorded neural responses as mice were presented with sequences of natural movie clips, aiming to understand how repeated exposure enables neural circuits to predict future sensory input based on past experience.

**Key aspects of the experiment:**
- Mice viewed repeating sequences of three different 2-second natural movie clips (labeled ‘A’, ‘B’, ‘C’), interleaved with a grey screen (‘X’).
- Recordings span multiple sessions: pre-training (random order), training (sequence learning), and post-training.
- Calcium imaging data were recorded simultaneously from eight fields-of-view per session, covering layers 2/3 and 4 in visual cortical areas (V1, LM, AM, PM).
- The mouse line used expresses GCaMP6f in excitatory neurons.

### Main Data Features

- Two-photon calcium imaging time-series data
- Multiple imaging planes and fields-of-view per experiment
- Associated image segmentation data (masks/ROIs, possibly with extracted traces)
- Layer and area information for fields-of-view
- Repeated stimulus presentations for robust analysis

### Subjects and Sessions

- 13 mice (Mus musculus)
- Over 1100 NWB files
- Each NWB file typically contains all imaging data for a specific session and field-of-view

### Potential Research Questions

- How does neural population activity evolve with sequence learning?
- Are predictive coding signals observable in visual cortical neurons?
- What are the differences in learning dynamics across layers (L2/3 vs L4) and areas (V1, LM, AM, PM)?
- How variable are single-neuron responses to repeated movie sequences?

- CC-BY-4.0 (open for reuse with attribution)
